## What is the current behavior?

Issue Number: http://b/214103351

Angular generates `goog.getMsg()` statements for JSCompiler which do _not_ contain any options.

```html
<div i18n>Hello, {{ name }}!</div>
```

Becomes:

```typescript
const MSG_XXX = goog.getMsg(
  // Message template.
  'Hello, {$interpolation}',
  // Message parameters.
  { interpolation': '...' },
);
```

## What is the new behavior?

Angular generates `goog.getMsg()` statements for JSCompiler which _do_ contain original code in the options. This is useful for identifying specific placeholders which are otherwise named `interpolation`. See http://b/219565887 for discussion of the new `goog.getMsg()` API.

```html
<div i18n>Hello, {{ name }}!</div>
```

Becomes:

```typescript
const MSG_XXX = goog.getMsg(
  // Message template.
  'Hello, {$interpolation}',
  // Message parameters.
  { interpolation': '...' },
  // Message options.
  {
    // Original code for each placeholder.
    original_code: {
      'interpolation': '{{ name }}',
    },
  },
);
```

